# Winsorize outliers at 1%/99% percentiles
winsor_thresholds = {}
rows_winsorized = {}

for col in ["revenue", "top"]:
    # Calculate percentiles
    lo, hi = df[col].quantile([0.01, 0.99])
    winsor_thresholds[col] = (float(lo), float(hi))
    
    # Count rows that will be affected
    rows_winsorized[col] = int(((df[col] < lo) | (df[col] > hi)).sum())
    
    # Apply winsorization
    df[col] = np.clip(df[col], lo, hi)
    
    print(f"{col}: winsorized {rows_winsorized[col]} rows at [{lo:.2f}, {hi:.2f}]")

# Create log-transformed revenue variable
df["log_rev"] = np.log1p(df["revenue"])
print(f"\nCreated log_rev variable (log(1 + revenue))")

# Show summary statistics
print(f"\nSummary statistics after cleaning:")
print(df[["revenue", "top", "log_rev"]].describe())

# Helper function for OLS regression with robust standard errors
def fit_ols(y, X):
    """Fit OLS model with robust (HC1) standard errors"""
    Xc = add_constant(X, has_constant="add")
    model = OLS(y, Xc).fit(cov_type="HC1")  # robust SEs
    return model

# Model 1: revenue ~ top (simple linear relationship)
print("Model 1: revenue ~ top")
m1 = fit_ols(df["revenue"], df[["top"]])
print(m1.summary())
print(f"\nModel 1 R-squared: {m1.rsquared:.4f}")
print(f"TOP coefficient: {m1.params.get('top', float('nan')):.4f}")

# Model 2: log1p(revenue) ~ spline(top, df=4) - Check for diminishing returns
print("Model 2: log1p(revenue) ~ spline(top, df=4)")
X_spline = dmatrix("bs(top, df=4, degree=3, include_intercept=False)", {"top": df["top"]}, return_type="dataframe")
m2 = fit_ols(df["log_rev"], X_spline)
print(f"Model 2 R-squared: {m2.rsquared:.4f}")

# Generate predictions for plotting
top_grid = np.linspace(df["top"].min(), df["top"].max(), 200)
Xgrid_spline = dmatrix("bs(top, df=4, degree=3, include_intercept=False)", {"top": top_grid}, return_type="dataframe")
Xgrid_spline_c = add_constant(Xgrid_spline, has_constant="add")
pred2 = m2.get_prediction(Xgrid_spline_c)
pred2_mean = pred2.predicted_mean
pred2_ci = pred2.conf_int()

# Generate Figure 2: Spline regression (uncontrolled)
plt.figure(figsize=(7,5), dpi=150)
plt.plot(top_grid, pred2_mean, 'b-', linewidth=2, label='Spline fit')
plt.fill_between(top_grid, pred2_ci[:,0], pred2_ci[:,1], alpha=0.2, color='blue', label='95% CI')
plt.xlabel("Time on Page (TOP)")
plt.ylabel("log(1 + Revenue)")
plt.title("Diminishing Returns Check (Spline, Uncontrolled)")

design = dmatrix(
    "bs(top, df=4, degree=3, include_intercept=False) + C(browser) + C(platform) + C(site)",
    df,
    return_type="dataframe"
)

# Marginal Effects Analysis
# Compare predictions at different TOP values while holding other factors constant

def predict_logrev(model, top_values, df_ref):
    """Predict log(revenue) for given TOP values, holding other factors at reference levels"""
    # Build a design matrix holding other factors at their reference (first category)
    tmp = df_ref.copy()
    tmp = tmp.iloc[:1].copy()  # single row template
    tmp = pd.concat([tmp]*len(top_values), ignore_index=True)
    tmp["top"] = top_values
    
    # Set reference categories to the first levels
    for col in ["browser","platform","site"]:
        if col in tmp.columns and str(tmp[col].dtype) == "category":
            tmp[col] = tmp[col].cat.categories[0]
    
    X = build_design_matrices([design_info], tmp)[0]
    Xc = add_constant(X, has_constant="add")
    pred = model.get_prediction(Xc).predicted_mean
    return pred

# Generate predictions across TOP range
top_vals = np.linspace(df["top"].quantile(0.05), df["top"].quantile(0.95), 120)
log_pred = predict_logrev(m3, top_vals, df)

# Generate Figure 3: Controlled marginal effects
plt.figure(figsize=(7,5), dpi=150)
plt.plot(top_vals, np.expm1(log_pred), 'g-', linewidth=2)
plt.xlabel("Time on Page (TOP)")
plt.ylabel("Predicted Revenue (Controlled)")
plt.title("Controlled Marginal Effect of TOP")
plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
plt.tight_layout()

# Save the figure
fig3_path = os.path.join(FIG_DIR, "fig3_marginal_effects.png")
plt.savefig(fig3_path)
print(f"Saved Figure 3: {fig3_path}")
plt.show()

# Advanced Analysis: Partial Dependence Plot and Effect Size Quantification
# Generate comprehensive effect size analysis at different percentiles

print(" ADVANCED EFFECT SIZE ANALYSIS")
print("="*50)

# Calculate effects at key percentiles
percentiles = [25, 50, 75, 90, 95]
top_percentiles = [df["top"].quantile(p/100) for p in percentiles]
effect_analysis = []

for i, p in enumerate(percentiles):
    top_val = top_percentiles[i]
    pred_val = predict_logrev(m3, np.array([top_val]), df)[0]
    revenue_pred = np.expm1(pred_val)
    
    effect_analysis.append({
        'percentile': p,
        'top_value': top_val,
        'predicted_revenue': revenue_pred
    })
    
    print(f"P{p:2d}: TOP={top_val:.2f}  Revenue=${revenue_pred:.4f}")

# Calculate incremental effects between percentiles
print(f"\n INCREMENTAL EFFECTS:")
baseline_revenue = effect_analysis[1]['predicted_revenue']  # P50 as baseline

for i in range(2, len(effect_analysis)):  # Start from P75
    current_revenue = effect_analysis[i]['predicted_revenue']
    pct_change = ((current_revenue - baseline_revenue) / baseline_revenue) * 100
    print(f"P50  P{effect_analysis[i]['percentile']}: {pct_change:+.2f}% revenue change")

# Elasticity calculation
mu = df["top"].mean()
log_mu = predict_logrev(m3, np.array([mu]), df)[0]
log_mu_110 = predict_logrev(m3, np.array([mu * 1.1]), df)[0]  # 10% increase in TOP

elasticity = (np.expm1(log_mu_110) - np.expm1(log_mu)) / np.expm1(log_mu) / 0.1
print(f"\n ELASTICITY: 1% increase in TOP  {elasticity:.3f}% change in revenue")

# Create advanced partial dependence plot
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15, 6), dpi=150)

# Left plot: Partial dependence with confidence intervals
top_fine_grid = np.linspace(df["top"].quantile(0.01), df["top"].quantile(0.99), 200)
log_pred_fine = predict_logrev(m3, top_fine_grid, df)
revenue_pred_fine = np.expm1(log_pred_fine)

ax1.plot(top_fine_grid, revenue_pred_fine, 'b-', linewidth=3, label='Partial Dependence')

# Add percentile markers
for i, effect in enumerate(effect_analysis):
    ax1.axvline(effect['top_value'], color='red', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    ax1.plot(effect['top_value'], effect['predicted_revenue'], 'ro', markersize=8)
    ax1.annotate(f"P{effect['percentile']}", 
                xy=(effect['top_value'], effect['predicted_revenue']),
                xytext=(5, 5), textcoords='offset points', fontsize=10)

ax1.set_xlabel("Time on Page (TOP)", fontsize=12)
ax1.set_ylabel("Predicted Revenue (Controlled)", fontsize=12)
ax1.set_title("Partial Dependence Plot with Percentile Markers", fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
ax1.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
ax1.legend()

# Right plot: Effect size by TOP range (corrected)
top_ranges = ['P50-P75', 'P50-P90', 'P50-P95']
effect_sizes = []

# Calculate effect sizes relative to P50
for i in range(2, len(effect_analysis)):  # Start from P75 (index 2)
    baseline_rev = effect_analysis[1]['predicted_revenue']  # P50
    curr_rev = effect_analysis[i]['predicted_revenue']
    effect_size = ((curr_rev - baseline_rev) / baseline_rev) * 100
    effect_sizes.append(effect_size)

colors = ['lightgreen', 'orange', 'lightcoral']
bars = ax2.bar(top_ranges, effect_sizes, color=colors)
ax2.set_ylabel("Revenue Change (%)", fontsize=12)
ax2.set_title("Marginal Effect by TOP Range", fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
ax2.grid(True, alpha=0.3, axis='y')

# Add value labels on bars
for bar, value in zip(bars, effect_sizes):
    height = bar.get_height()
    ax2.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2., height + 0.1,
             f'{value:+.2f}%', ha='center', va='bottom', fontweight='bold')

plt.tight_layout()

# Save the advanced analysis figure
fig4_path = os.path.join(FIG_DIR, "fig4_advanced_effects.png")
plt.savefig(fig4_path, bbox_inches='tight', facecolor='white')
print(f"\nSaved Advanced Effects Figure: {fig4_path}")
plt.show()

median_revenue = np.expm1(median_pred)
p75_revenue = np.expm1(p75_pred)
percent_improvement = ((p75_revenue - median_revenue) / median_revenue) * 100
